Import CSV

full_data <- read_csv('~/Downloads/flavors_of_cacao.csv')

View dataset columns

You can see the column name include space and line break. If we dont clean that it might cause error in ggplot.

Clean columns name format

# Remove and replace spaces and line breaks
names(full_data) <- tolower(gsub(pattern = '[[:space:]+]', '_', names(full_data)))

# View the new column names 
names(full_data)
## [1] "company_(maker-if_known)"        "specific_bean_origin_or_bar_name"
## [3] "ref"                              "review_date"                     
## [5] "cocoa_percent"                    "company_location"                
## [7] "rating"                           "bean_type"                       
## [9] "broad_bean_origin"

Cocoa percentage

# 
full_data$cocoa_percent_numeric <- as.numeric(sub("%", "", full_data$cocoa_percent)) / 100

# 10%
ggplot(data = full_data) + 
  geom_jitter(mapping = aes(x = review_date, y = cocoa_percent_numeric)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1), labels = scales::percent)

Try rworldmap

learning YANGYAs code, Its not teach in courseras course.

omap <- group_by(full_data,broad_bean_origin)
omap1 <- summarise(omap,broad_bean_origin)
## Warning: Returning more (or less) than 1 row per `summarise()` group was deprecated in
## dplyr 1.1.0.
##  Please use `reframe()` instead.
##  When switching from `summarise()` to `reframe()`, remember that `reframe()`
##   always returns an ungrouped data frame and adjust accordingly.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'broad_bean_origin'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.
map2 <- joinCountryData2Map(omap1,joinCode="NAME",nameJoinColumn = "broad_bean_origin")
## 1555 codes from your data successfully matched countries in the map
## 240 codes from your data failed to match with a country code in the map
## 196 codes from the map weren't represented in your data
mapCountryData(map2,  mapTitle = "Cocao Origin Distribution", colourPalette = "negpos8")

Company location

This value means where the chocolate manufacture company base at.

cmap <- group_by(full_data,company_location)
cmap1 <- summarise(cmap,count=n())
map3 <- joinCountryData2Map(cmap1,joinCode="NAME",nameJoinColumn = "company_location")
## 51 codes from your data successfully matched countries in the map
## 9 codes from your data failed to match with a country code in the map
## 192 codes from the map weren't represented in your data
mapCountryData(map3,nameColumnToPlot = "count", mapTitle = "Chocolate Factory Distribution", colourPalette = "negpos8")
